    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Internal economic stratification and elite overreach eroded the redistributive palace economies, causing systemic fragility that external raids merely exploited.\", \"mechanism\": \"Endogenous decay of centralized redistribution systems created food shortages and depopulation, making societies vulnerable to opportunistic raiding rather than coordinated invasion.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Cyprus (where copper trade continued uninterrupted)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Linear B tablets from Pylos showing grain surplus and military provisioning in the year immediately before destruction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant shifts causality from external military coordination to internal economic collapse, treating Sea Peoples as scavengers rather than conquerors.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A pandemic of unknown origin swept through Eastern Mediterranean populations, decimating labor forces and military recruitment pools, which the Sea Peoples' movements merely followed into already-weakened territories.\", \"mechanism\": \"Demographic collapse from infectious disease reduced agricultural output and emptied garrison forts, creating power vacuums that maritime migrants filled without significant resistance.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Inland settlements above 1000m elevation\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Mass grave sites in the Levant with preserved pathogen DNA inconsistent with epidemic spread patterns\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant substitutes coordinated military pressure with epidemiological causation, reframing Sea Peoples as demographic successors rather than destroyers.\"}"
    },
