      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Climate-induced megadrought triggered cascading agricultural failures across the Eastern Mediterranean, forcing entire populations to become maritime refugees who overwhelmed coastal cities.\", \"mechanism\": \"Multi-decadal precipitation decline caused harvest collapse and famine, transforming sedentary farmers into desperate seaborne migrants whose mass movement destabilized receiving regions.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Nile Delta (sustained by flood-irrigation independent of rainfall)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Pollen core samples from Lake Huleh showing stable Mediterranean woodland during 1200–1150 BC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant replaces military raiding with climate migration as the causal mechanism, recasting Sea Peoples as victims of environmental collapse.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The diffusion of iron-smelting technology disrupted the bronze-based trade monopolies of palace elites, empowering peripheral groups who became the Sea Peoples and dismantled the old order.\", \"mechanism\": \"Technological substitution in weaponry and tools broke the economic leverage of tin-and-copper controlling states, enabling decentralized maritime groups to challenge and defeat bronze-equipped armies.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt (which rapidly adopted iron after repelling attacks)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Metallurgical analysis of Sea Peoples weaponry from Ashkelon showing exclusively bronze composition\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant substitutes trade disruption with technological revolution as the driver, making iron the causal agent rather than coordinated raids.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A systemic collapse of inter-palatial diplomatic networks preceded and enabled Sea Peoples raids, as former allies refused mutual defense obligations and left individual kingdoms isolated.\", \"mechanism\": \"Breakdown of treaty-based reciprocity among great powers eliminated coordinated military response, allowing small maritime bands to defeat isolated garrisons that expected reinforcements which never came.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Assyria (which maintained independent diplomatic channels)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Amarna-style diplomatic correspondence between Ugarit and Hatti dated post-1200 BC confirming active mutual defense pacts\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant shifts the mechanism from external military pressure to diplomatic failure, making the Sea Peoples a trigger rather than the primary cause.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Seismic catastrophe destroyed multiple Eastern Mediterranean urban centers within a single generation, and the Sea Peoples were displaced survivors of these earthquakes rather than their cause.\", \"mechanism\": \"A tectonic event cluster collapsed fortifications, granaries, and ports across the region, creating homeless populations who took to the sea and were misidentified as invaders by Egyptian records.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Settlements on non-seismic Arabian Shield\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Destruction layers at Tiryns showing arrowheads and sling stones embedded in collapsed walls, indicating combat not earthquake\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant substitutes human agency with geophysical causation, recasting Sea Peoples as refugees of natural disaster.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The Sea Peoples were not a cause of collapse but a consequence: piracy and migration increased because existing states had already weakened from internal revolts by disenfranchised mercenary classes.\", \"mechanism\": \"Palace reliance on foreign mercenaries created armed, organized groups within societies; when payment failed during economic downturns, these mercenaries revolted and seized coastal strongholds, later appearing in records as Sea Peoples.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt (where mercenary revolts were suppressed by Ramesses III)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Payroll records from Pylos confirming full mercenary compensation in the year of destruction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant inverts the causal arrow: internal mercenary revolt precedes and produces the Sea Peoples phenomenon, rather than external invasion causing internal collapse.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The Sea Peoples were a literary invention of Ramesses III's propagandists, conflating disparate local conflicts into a single narrative of foreign invasion to legitimize the Egyptian throne.\", \"mechanism\": \"Royal inscriptions at Medinet Habu fabricated a unified enemy to glorify the pharaoh's military achievements, when in reality the Eastern Mediterranean collapsed from unrelated local causes that Egypt later exploited for ideological purposes.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egyptian royal ideology and historiography\"], \"excludes\": [\"Archaeological evidence of actual destruction events in the Levant and Anatolia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Non-Egyptian textual sources from Ugarit and Hatti independently referencing Sea Peoples attacks before 1177 BC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This variant substitutes the entire causal framework with an epistemological critique, treating the Sea Peoples as a discursive construct rather than a historical force.\"}"
